## Data Model (Redis Enterprise)

The cluster is the central abstraction. Each cluster represents a single semantic learning regardless of where it currently exists.

```
cluster:<id> (HASH)
  text             canonical statement of the learning
  embedding_id     pointer to RediSearch HNSW index entry
  status           draft | promoted | superseded
  current_layer    enterprise | org-user | stack | repo:<name> | auto-memory
  promoted_to      <layer> when applicable
  promoted_at      timestamp
  promoted_pr      URL of the PR that landed it
  created_at       timestamp

cluster:<id>:occurrences  (LIST)   raw occurrences for audit + velocity scoring
cluster:<id>:repos        (SET)    repos where it has appeared
cluster:<id>:supersedes   (SET)    prior cluster IDs this replaced
cluster:<id>:tags         (SET)    taxonomy tags from classifier

queue:triage      (ZSET)  cluster IDs scored by weighted occurrence count
queue:fast-track  (ZSET)  clusters above velocity threshold
queue:cleanup     (ZSET)  superseded clusters needing downstream cleanup

repo:<name>:rules        (HASH)  rule file path -> cluster ID
repo:<name>:claude_md    (HASH)  CLAUDE.md section -> cluster ID
org:rules                (HASH)  ~/.claude/rules/* -> cluster ID
enterprise:rules         (HASH)  managed CLAUDE.md sections -> cluster ID

embeddings (RediSearch HNSW index)
  field: embedding (vector)
  field: cluster_id (tag)
  field: layer (tag)
```

The `*:rules` indices are the key to cleanup. When a cluster gets promoted to a higher layer, you query the lower-layer indices for that cluster ID and queue cleanup PRs for every match.

**No engineer identity is stored.** The velocity signal comes from raw occurrence count weighted by source type, not engineer-distinct counts. API Gateway access logs (via SigV4 from IAM Identity Center) provide audit trail of who promoted what without polluting the cluster data.

